I tested the code in Rainier system.

The power supply device driver abstracts the 'pmbus LED' and represents it as a standard /sys/class/leds/ LED. From the user space code perspective, this power supply LED, which essentially receives i2c/pmbus commands to set its behavior, appears just like any other LED.

Power supply LEDs in Rainier:

cffps2-68:
cffps2-69:
cffps2-6a:
cffps2-6b:

This isn't enough of a test.  This needs to verify that the LED is attached to the PSU, which it needs to be doing via the association, not simply checking if element exists.

Also, this is checking if a Chassis or Board interface exists, not whether a PowerSupply interface exists.

In the getValidPowerSupplyPath call within powerSupplyPatchAfterValidateChassis, it verifies the existence of the PowerSupply interface.

In setLocationIndicatorActive, it checks if the LED is associated with the PSU via the association.
https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/57765/56/redfish-core/lib/led.hpp#278

We do both checks

Validate Power Supply:
https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/42221/31/redfish-core/lib/power_supply.hpp#159

Check LED Group path via the association at:
https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/42221/33/redfish-core/lib/led.hpp#332

>  it verifies the existence of the PowerSupply interface.

Right, I asked to verify that the led is attached to THIS SPECIFIC power supply, not just that a power supply exists.

> In setLocationIndicatorActive, it checks if the LED is associated with the PSU via the association.

Then this check on this line is redundant?
This check is necessary because we must validate the chassis and power supply path before verifying whether the LED is attached to the power supply.
